---
/*
  vlm-pipeline.astro — Project detail page for the VLM Pipeline project.

  HOW TO ADD MORE PROJECT PAGES:
  1. Duplicate this file (e.g. copy it to "my-new-project.astro")
  2. Change the content (title, description, sections)
  3. Update the href in the ProjectCard on index.astro to point to it
  4. That's it! The URL will be /projects/my-new-project/
*/

import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="VLM Pipeline — Yannick den Boer">
  <Nav />

  <div class="project-page">
    <a href="/" class="project-page-back">&larr; Back to home</a>

    <h1>Vision-Language Model Pipeline for Behavioral Cue Classification</h1>

    <div class="project-page-meta">
      <span class="tag accent">VLM</span>
      <span class="tag">PyTorch</span>
      <span class="tag">HuggingFace</span>
      <span class="tag">Research</span>
      <span class="tag">OpenCV</span>
    </div>

    <div class="project-page-content">
      <p>
        This was my MSc AI thesis project at Utrecht University, conducted in collaboration with UMC Utrecht's neonatal department. The goal was to explore whether modern Vision-Language Models could automatically classify behavioral cues in preterm infants from video recordings.
      </p>

      <h2>The Problem</h2>
      <p>
        Clinical assessment of preterm infant behavior is currently done manually by trained observers. This process is time-consuming and subjective. Automating parts of this assessment could help clinicians work faster and more consistently.
      </p>

      <h2>My Approach</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Designed a multi-stage pipeline: video preprocessing with OpenCV, frame extraction, and VLM-based classification</li>
        <li>Evaluated multiple Vision-Language Models from HuggingFace for their ability to interpret clinical video frames</li>
        <li>Built custom data loaders and evaluation metrics in PyTorch</li>
        <li>Worked closely with clinical staff to validate the approach against expert annotations</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Results</h2>
      <p>
        The pipeline showed promising results for certain behavioral cue categories, demonstrating that VLMs can extract clinically relevant information from neonatal video recordings. The work contributed to ongoing research at UMC Utrecht's neonatal care unit.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
